  <title>Choice of Flood Quantile Estimator</title>

  <para>In general, the estimation of a design quantile should be guided by the consequences of
    over<?oxy_delete author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T152902+1100" content="-"?> and
    under-design (Slack <emphasis>et al</emphasis>., 1975).<?oxy_insert_start author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T152907+1100"?>
    <?oxy_insert_end?>This section considers the following question: Given data D, what is the best
    estimate of the flood discharge which has an AEP of
    X%<?oxy_insert_start author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T152919+1100"?>?<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T152919+1100" content="."?></para>

  <para>If the true value of <inlineequation>
      <m:math display="inline">
        <m:mi>θ</m:mi>
      </m:math>
    </inlineequation> were known, then the pdf <inlineequation>
      <m:math display="inline">
        <m:mi>p(q|θ)</m:mi>
      </m:math>
    </inlineequation> can be used to compute the flood quantile
  <inlineequation>
      <m:math display="inline">
        <m:mrow>
          <m:msub>
            <m:mi>q</m:mi>

            <m:mi>Y</m:mi>
          </m:msub>

          <m:mo>(θ)</m:mo>
        </m:mrow>
      </m:math>
    </inlineequation>. For AM series the quantile with an AEP of X% is defined
  as:</para>

  <equation xml:id="b3_ch2_e_aq26s">
    <m:math display="block">
      <m:mrow>
        <m:mrow>
          <m:mo>P(q&gt;</m:mo>

          <m:msub>
            <m:mi>q</m:mi>

            <m:mi>Y</m:mi>
          </m:msub>

          <m:mi>∣θ</m:mi>
        </m:mrow>

        <m:mo>)=</m:mo>

        <m:mrow>
          <m:mfrac>
            <m:mi>1</m:mi>

            <m:mi>Y</m:mi>
          </m:mfrac>

          <m:mrow>
            <m:mo>=</m:mo>

            <m:mrow>
              <m:munderover>
                <m:mo>∫</m:mo>

                <m:msub>
                  <m:mi>q</m:mi>

                  <m:mi>Y</m:mi>
                </m:msub>

                <m:mi>∞</m:mi>
              </m:munderover>

              <m:mi>p(q∣θ</m:mi>
            </m:mrow>
          </m:mrow>

          <m:mi>)dq</m:mi>
        </m:mrow>
      </m:mrow>
    </m:math>
  </equation>

  <para>However, in practice the true value of <inlineequation>
      <m:math display="inline">
        <m:mi>θ</m:mi>
      </m:math>
    </inlineequation> (as well as the distribution family) is unknown. All
  that is known about <inlineequation>
      <m:math display="inline">
        <m:mi>θ</m:mi>
      </m:math>
    </inlineequation>, given the data D, is summarized by a probability
  distribution with pdf <inlineequation>
      <m:math display="inline">
        <m:mi>p(θ|D)</m:mi>
      </m:math>
    </inlineequation>. <xref linkend="b3_ch2_s6"/> describes how this
  distribution may be obtained – this distribution is the posterior
  distribution if performing a Bayesian analysis or the sampling distribution
  if performing a bootstrap analysis.</para>

  <para>If the true value of <inlineequation>
      <m:math display="inline">
        <m:mi>θ</m:mi>
      </m:math>
    </inlineequation> is not known, it follows that the true value of the
  quantile <inlineequation>
      <m:math display="inline">
        <m:mi>p(θ|D)</m:mi>
      </m:math>
    </inlineequation> is not known. The uncertainty about <inlineequation>
      <m:math display="inline">
        <m:mi>θ</m:mi>
      </m:math>
    </inlineequation> described by the pdf <inlineequation>
      <m:math display="inline">
        <m:mi>p(θ|D)</m:mi>
      </m:math>
    </inlineequation> , translates into uncertainty about the quantile,
  described by the quantile predictive pdf <inlineequation>
      <m:math display="inline">
        <m:mrow>
          <m:mi>p(</m:mi>

          <m:mrow>
            <m:msub>
              <m:mi>q</m:mi>

              <m:mi>Y</m:mi>
            </m:msub>

            <m:mo>|D)</m:mo>
          </m:mrow>
        </m:mrow>
      </m:math>
    </inlineequation>. The question then arises, which value from the quantile
  predictive pdf <inlineequation>
      <m:math display="inline">
        <m:mrow>
          <m:mi>p(</m:mi>

          <m:msub>
            <m:mi>q</m:mi>

            <m:mi>Y</m:mi>
          </m:msub>

          <m:mi>|</m:mi>

          <m:mo>D)</m:mo>
        </m:mrow>
      </m:math>
    </inlineequation>should be adopted as the flood quantile estimate? This
  section presents two approaches for determining the best estimate of a flood
  discharge with a X% AEP knowing the pdf <inlineequation>
      <m:math display="inline">
        <m:mrow>
          <m:mi>p(</m:mi>

          <m:msub>
            <m:mi>q</m:mi>

            <m:mi>Y</m:mi>
          </m:msub>

          <m:mi>|</m:mi>

          <m:mo>D)</m:mo>
        </m:mrow>
      </m:math>
    </inlineequation>.</para>

  <section xml:id="b3_ch2_s_sw7yg">
    <title>Expected Parameter Quantiles</title>

    <para>This section considers the case where the consequence of
      over<?oxy_delete author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162301+1100" content="-"?> and
      under-design is expressed by some measure of the difference between the true and estimated X%
      AEP quantiles – this difference is called the quantile error.</para>

    <para>The loss function <inlineequation>
        <m:math display="inline">
          <m:mrow>
            <m:mi>L(</m:mi>

            <m:msub>
              <m:mi>q</m:mi>

              <m:mi>Y</m:mi>
            </m:msub>

            <m:mrow>
              <m:mi>(D),</m:mi>

              <m:mrow>
                <m:msub>
                  <m:mi>q</m:mi>

                  <m:mi>Y</m:mi>
                </m:msub>

                <m:mo>(θ)]</m:mo>
              </m:mrow>
            </m:mrow>
          </m:mrow>
        </m:math>
      </inlineequation> describes the loss or consequence when the true
    quantile <inlineequation>
        <m:math display="inline">
          <m:mrow>
            <m:msub>
              <m:mi>q</m:mi>

              <m:mi>Y</m:mi>
            </m:msub>

            <m:mo>(θ),</m:mo>
          </m:mrow>
        </m:math>
      </inlineequation> which depends on <inlineequation>
        <m:math display="inline">
          <m:mi>θ</m:mi>
        </m:math>
      </inlineequation>, is incorrectly estimated by <inlineequation>
        <m:math display="inline">
          <m:mrow>
            <m:msub>
              <m:mi>q</m:mi>

              <m:mi>Y</m:mi>
            </m:msub>

            <m:mo>(D),</m:mo>
          </m:mrow>
        </m:math>
      </inlineequation> which depends on the data D. Because the true value of
    <inlineequation>
        <m:math display="inline">
          <m:mi>θ</m:mi>
        </m:math>
      </inlineequation> is uncertain, the best estimator <inlineequation>
        <m:math display="inline">
          <m:mrow>
            <m:msub>
              <m:mi>q</m:mi>

              <m:mi>Y</m:mi>
            </m:msub>

            <m:msub>
              <m:mi>(D)</m:mi>

              <m:mi>opt</m:mi>
            </m:msub>
          </m:mrow>
        </m:math>
      </inlineequation> is the one that minimises the expected loss:</para>

    <equation xml:id="b3_ch2_e_uko3q">
      <m:math display="block">
        <m:mrow>
          <m:msub>
            <m:mi>q</m:mi>

            <m:mi>Y</m:mi>
          </m:msub>

          <m:msub>
            <m:mi>(D)</m:mi>

            <m:mi>opt</m:mi>
          </m:msub>

          <m:mi>←</m:mi>

          <m:mo>min</m:mo>

          <m:mrow>
            <m:munderover>
              <m:mo>∫</m:mo>

              <m:mi>θ</m:mi>

              <m:mi/>
            </m:munderover>

            <m:mi>L[</m:mi>
          </m:mrow>

          <m:msub>
            <m:mi>q</m:mi>

            <m:mi>Y</m:mi>
          </m:msub>

          <m:mrow>
            <m:mi>(D),</m:mi>

            <m:msub>
              <m:mi>q</m:mi>

              <m:mi>Y</m:mi>
            </m:msub>

            <m:mi>(θ)]p(θ|D)dθ</m:mi>
          </m:mrow>
        </m:mrow>
      </m:math>
    </equation>

    <para>The optimal quantile estimator depends on the choice of loss
    function.</para>

    <section xml:id="b3_ch2_s_x9c77">
      <title>Quadratic loss</title>

      <para>The quadratic loss function may be appropriate when the consequences of
        under<?oxy_delete author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162346+1100" content="-"?> or
        over<?oxy_insert_start author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162350+1100"?>-<?oxy_insert_end?>design
        are judged to be
        <?oxy_delete author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162356+1100" content="the "?>same
        and
        <?oxy_delete author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162358+1100" content="the "?>loss
        is proportional to the square of the quantile error. The loss function is expressed
          as:<equation xml:id="b3_ch2_e_oxco0">
          <m:math display="block">
            <m:mrow>
              <m:mi>L</m:mi>
              <m:mrow>
                <m:mo>[</m:mo>
                <m:mrow>
                  <m:msub>
                    <m:mi>q</m:mi>
                    <m:mi>Y</m:mi>
                  </m:msub>
                  <m:mrow>
                    <m:mo>(</m:mo>
                    <m:mi>D</m:mi>
                    <m:mo>)</m:mo>
                  </m:mrow>
                  <m:mo>,</m:mo>
                  <m:msub>
                    <m:mi>q</m:mi>
                    <m:mi>Y</m:mi>
                  </m:msub>
                  <m:mrow>
                    <m:mo>(</m:mo>
                    <m:mi>&#x03B8;</m:mi>
                    <m:mo>)</m:mo>
                  </m:mrow>
                </m:mrow>
                <m:mo>]</m:mo>
              </m:mrow>
              <m:mo>&#x221D;</m:mo>
              <m:msup>
                <m:mrow>
                  <m:mrow>
                    <m:mo>[</m:mo>
                    <m:mrow>
                      <m:msub>
                        <m:mi>q</m:mi>
                        <m:mi>Y</m:mi>
                      </m:msub>
                      <m:mrow>
                        <m:mo>(</m:mo>
                        <m:mi>D</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>)</m:mo>
                      </m:mrow>
                      <m:mo>&#x2212;</m:mo>
                      <m:msub>
                        <m:mi>q</m:mi>
                        <m:mi>Y</m:mi>
                      </m:msub>
                      <m:mrow>
                        <m:mo>(</m:mo>
                        <m:mi>&#x03B8;</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>)</m:mo>
                      </m:mrow>
                    </m:mrow>
                    <m:mo>]</m:mo>
                  </m:mrow>
                </m:mrow>
                <m:mn>2</m:mn>
              </m:msup>
            </m:mrow>
          </m:math>
        </equation></para>

      <para>The expected value of this loss function is
        <?oxy_delete author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162413+1100" content="commonly "?>referred
        to as the Mean Squared Error
        (MSE)<?oxy_delete author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162431+1100" content=". It "?><?oxy_insert_start author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162433+1100"?>,
        which <?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162459+1100" content="can be "?>show<?oxy_insert_start author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162500+1100"?>s<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162500+1100" content="n"?>
        <?oxy_insert_start author="RadhikaChhotai" timestamp="20151022T162454+1100"?>that
        <?oxy_insert_end?>the optimal quantile estimator is the expected value of qY(D) (DeGroot,
        1970):</para>

      <para><equation xml:id="b3_ch2_e_s97qk">
          <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
            <semantics>
              <mrow>
                <mi>E</mi>
                <mrow>
                  <mo>[</mo>
                  <mrow>
                    <msub>
                      <mi>q</mi>
                      <mi>Y</mi>
                    </msub>
                    <mo>&#x007C;</mo>
                    <mi>D</mi>
                  </mrow>
                  <mo>]</mo>
                </mrow>
                <mo>=</mo>
                <munderover>
                  <mstyle mathsize="140%" displaystyle="true">
                    <mo>&#x222B;</mo>
                  </mstyle>
                  <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
                  <mrow/>
                </munderover>
                <msub>
                  <mi>q</mi>
                  <mi>Y</mi>
                </msub>
                <mrow>
                  <mo>(</mo>
                  <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
                  <mo>)</mo>
                </mrow>
                <mi>p</mi>
                <mrow>
                  <mo>(</mo>
                  <mrow>
                    <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
                    <mo>&#x007C;</mo>
                    <mi>D</mi>
                  </mrow>
                  <mo>)</mo>
                </mrow>
                <mi>d</mi>
                <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
              </mrow>
              <annotation encoding="MathType-MTEF">MathType@MTEF@5@5@+=
                feaagKart1ev2aaatCvAUfeBSjuyZL2yd9gzLbvyNv2CaerbuLwBLn
                hiov2DGi1BTfMBaeXatLxBI9gBaerbd9wDYLwzYbItLDharqqtubsr
                4rNCHbGeaGqiVu0Je9sqqrpepC0xbbL8F4rqqrFfpeea0xe9Lq=Jc9
                vqaqpepm0xbba9pwe9Q8fs0=yqaqpepae9pg0FirpepeKkFr0xfr=x
                fr=xb9adbaqaaeGaciGaaiaabeqaamaabaabaaGcbaaeaaaaaaaaa8
                qacaWGfbWaamWaaeaacaWGXbWdamaaBaaaleaapeGaamywaaWdaeqa
                aOWdbiaacYhacaWGebaacaGLBbGaayzxaaGaeyypa0ZaaybCaeqal8
                aabaWdbiabeI7aXbWdaeaaa0qaa8qacqGHRiI8aaGccaWGXbWdamaa
                BaaaleaapeGaamywaaWdaeqaaOWdbmaabmaabaGaeqiUdehacaGLOa
                GaayzkaaGaamiCamaabmaabaGaeqiUdeNaaiiFaiaadseaaiaawIca
                caGLPaaacaWGKbGaeqiUdehaaa@507B@ </annotation>
            </semantics>
          </math>
        </equation></para>

      <para>Stedinger (1983) observes that this integral may not exist for
      some of the probability distributions used in Flood Frequency Analysis.
      To avoid this problem the following first-order approximation may be
      used:</para>

      <para><equation xml:id="b3_ch2_e_m9gsz">
          <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
            <semantics>
              <mrow>
                <mi>E</mi>
                <mrow>
                  <mo>[</mo>
                  <mrow>
                    <msub>
                      <mi>q</mi>
                      <mi>Y</mi>
                    </msub>
                    <mo>&#x007C;</mo>
                    <mi>D</mi>
                  </mrow>
                  <mo>]</mo>
                </mrow>
                <mo>=</mo>
                <msub>
                  <mi>q</mi>
                  <mi>Y</mi>
                </msub>
                <mrow>
                  <mo>[</mo>
                  <mrow>
                    <mi>E</mi>
                    <mrow>
                      <mo>(</mo>
                      <mrow>
                        <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
                        <mo>&#x007C;</mo>
                        <mi>D</mi>
                      </mrow>
                      <mo>)</mo>
                    </mrow>
                  </mrow>
                  <mo>]</mo>
                </mrow>
              </mrow>
              <annotation encoding="MathType-MTEF">MathType@MTEF@5@5@+=
                feaagKart1ev2aaatCvAUfeBSjuyZL2yd9gzLbvyNv2CaerbuLwBLn
                hiov2DGi1BTfMBaeXatLxBI9gBaerbd9wDYLwzYbItLDharqqtubsr
                4rNCHbGeaGqiVu0Je9sqqrpepC0xbbL8F4rqqrFfpeea0xe9Lq=Jc9
                vqaqpepm0xbba9pwe9Q8fs0=yqaqpepae9pg0FirpepeKkFr0xfr=x
                fr=xb9adbaqaaeGaciGaaiaabeqaamaabaabaaGcbaaeaaaaaaaaa8
                qacaWGfbWaamWaaeaacaWGXbWdamaaBaaaleaapeGaamywaaWdaeqa
                aOWdbiaacYhacaWGebaacaGLBbGaayzxaaGaeyypa0JaamyCa8aada
                WgaaWcbaWdbiaadMfaa8aabeaakmaadmaabaGaamyra8qadaqadaqa
                aiabeI7aXjaacYhacaWGebaacaGLOaGaayzkaaaapaGaay5waiaaw2 faaaaa@4804@ </annotation>
            </semantics>
          </math>
        </equation></para>

      <para>where <inlineequation>
          <m:math display="inline">
            <m:mi>E(θ|D)</m:mi>
          </m:math>
        </inlineequation> is the expected parameter given the data D:</para>

      <equation xml:id="b3_ch2_e_p4y0l">
        <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
          <semantics>
            <mrow>
              <mi>E</mi>
              <mrow>
                <mo>[</mo>
                <mrow>
                  <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
                  <mo>&#x007C;</mo>
                  <mi>D</mi>
                </mrow>
                <mo>]</mo>
              </mrow>
              <mo>=</mo>
              <mo>&#x222B;</mo>
              <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
              <mi>p</mi>
              <mrow>
                <mo>(</mo>
                <mrow>
                  <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
                  <mo>&#x007C;</mo>
                  <mi>D</mi>
                </mrow>
                <mo>)</mo>
              </mrow>
              <mi>d</mi>
              <mi>&#x03B8;</mi>
            </mrow>
            <annotation encoding="MathType-MTEF">MathType@MTEF@5@5@+=
